Introduction

In this report, our group focused on the trend of water temperature from 2014 to 2017 in the Lake Michigan beachfront of Chicago. Since climate change has been posing an increasingly challenging risk to the planet, we want to observe how a specific body of water has been affected in a few short years, and how temperature correlates to other variables in the lake. We believe that water average temperature will increase from 2014 to 2017, and it will change the other variables studied.

Background Section:

Chicago is located in the Midwest of the United States, on the Lake Michigan lakefront, along this area, there are beaches, parks and other attractions. Water temperature is a physical property expressing how hot or cold water is, and rapid temperature increase in Lake Michigan might have an adverse effect on aspects of the lake. A general consensus among climate scientists is that average temperature of the Earth is changing, but this might vary in different areas and different ecosystems. In this report, we are going to focus on how water temperature correlates to aspects of Lake Michigan, as well as the trends between independent variables overtime. We examine hourly records to find trends and correlations over time. Beach Water Quality records date back to May 15, 2014, and continue to be updated presently, seemingly on a yearly basis. The Beach Water Quality dataset has been collected by the Chicago Park District, maintaining sensors in the water at beaches along Chicagos Lake Michigan lakefront. Sensor locations change from time to time, though, due to the Park Districts operational needs (mainly water quality). Further, during some seasons and at some times, information from the sensors may not be available. As such, we chose not to include 2013 in our set, as there wasnt enough data present to make any significant conclusions. Other significant variables of interest are beach name, water temperature, turbidity, wave height, and wave period. We will use all of the other variables in order to observe any trends from beach to beach, allowing us to make significant conclusions if the data follows similar trends despite occurring at different locations. We will use the water temperature (measured in Celsius), turbidity (a measurement of how cloudy the water is), the height of the wave, and the period (distance between the waves) of the wave, in order to make observations about each beach, as well as any changes that take place as hours, seasons, and years pass.

Key Variables from the Beach Water Quality dataset
Name Description
beach Name of the beach data is collected at
time Time the data was collected at
temp Temperature of the water
turbidity Turbidity (cloudiness) of the water
wave_height Height of the waves (measured in meters)
wave_period Period (distance between peaks) of the waves (measured in meters

beach1 = beach %>% mutate(date_mdy = str_match(date, "\\d+.\\d+.\\d+")) %>% mutate(time = str_match(date, "\\s.+")) %>% mutate(date = mdy(date_mdy)) %>% select(-date_mdy) %>% filter(!(wave_height < 0)) %>% filter(!(wave_period < 0)) %>% filter(!(water_temp == 0)) %>%  mutate(year = year(date), month = month(date), day = day(date)) %>% filter(!(year == 2013)) %>% filter(beach_name == "Ohio Street Beach") %>% filter(!(month == 5)) %>% select(-trans_depth) %>% drop_na() %>% select(beach_name, year, month, day ,water_temp, wave_period, wave_height, turbidity)

Two Sided T Test Against the water temperature mean in 2014 and 2017:

Test the hypothesis that the mean water temperature are equal in 2014 and 2017 versus the two-sided alternative that they are not.

  1. Define parameters and a model

XiF1(1,1) YiF2(2,2)

  1. State hypotheses

Null Hypothesis H0:1=2 Alternative Hypothesis Ha:12

beach_analysis = beach1 %>% filter(year == 2014 | year == 2017) %>% group_by(year) %>% summarize(n = n(), water_temp_avg = mean(water_temp), std = sd(water_temp), se = std/sqrt(n)) %>% mutate(t.975 = qt(.975, n-1)) %>% mutate(lower = water_temp_avg - t.975*se) %>% mutate(high = water_temp_avg + t.975*se)
#mutate(std = sd(water_temp)) %>% select(water_temp, std)

Interpreatation:

We are 95 % confident that water temperature in year 2014 is between 19.73301 and 19.95280. We are also 95 % confident that water temperature in year 2017 is between 1.960955 and 20.88283

beach_2014_mean = beach1 %>% filter(year == 2014) %>% pull(water_temp)
beach_2017_mean = beach1 %>% filter(year == 2017) %>% pull(water_temp)
t.test(beach_2014_mean, beach_2017_mean)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  beach_2014_mean and beach_2017_mean
## t = -12.171, df = 4298.7, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.0873763 -0.7856748
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  19.84291  20.77943

Interpretation:

There is very strong evidence (p-value < 2.2e-16, two-sided t-test) that the average water temperature of 2014 and 2017 are not equal.

Graph:

gt(4298.7, a = -5, b = 5) +
  geom_t_fill(96.396, a = -15, b = -12.171) +
  geom_t_fill(96.396, a = 12.171, b = 15) +
  xlab("t statistic") +
  ggtitle("P-value visualization",
          subtitle = "4298.7 df, t = -12.171") +
  theme_minimal()

Discussion

We were able to find our p value, which was 2.2e-16. From this, we can suggest that there are in fact statistically significant differences between the average temperature of Lake Michigans waterfront in 2014 and 2017. A potential shortcoming in this data set could be some of the inconsistencies between years, including the difference between amount of data recorded for 2014, 2002, versus 2017, which was 2397. While they were recorded over the same months of the year, there might have been issues with recording data leading to differences in amount recorded each year. In conclusion, we found that there is potential evidence that there is a difference in the means between 2014 and 2017.

Analyzing correlation between water temperature and wave height

We used a linear regression model to try to fit and find a some kind of correlation between water temperature and wave height.

beach_lm = lm(wave_height~water_temp, data = beach1)
cf = coef(beach_lm)
slope = cf[2]
intercept = cf[1]
resid = residuals(beach_lm)
summary(beach_lm)

Graph

beach_line = beach1 %>% mutate(pred = (water_temp*slope) + intercept)  %>% mutate(resid = resid)

beach_line %>% ggplot(aes(x = water_temp, y = wave_height)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(aes(slope = slope, intercept =intercept), color = "blue")+
  xlab("water temperature") +
  ylab("wave height") +
  ggtitle("Correlation between water temperature and wave height")

Interpretation

This graph shows that the linear regression model has a weak and negative correlation. A lot of the points are far off from the predicted value from the line. Thus this shows the linear regression model fail to fit into the relationship between water temperature and wave height.

Residual Graph

beach_line %>% ggplot(aes(x = water_temp, y = resid))+
  geom_point() +
  xlab("water temperature") +
  ylab("Residuals") +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept=0), color="red", linetype = "dashed") +
  ggtitle("Residual plot")

Interpretation

From this residual plot, we could see that water temperature from 14 to 22 is usually over estimated, having a residual value larger than 0.1. The constant over estimation of this linear regression model shows that the estimation is off.

Discussion

In this graph, we analyze the relationship between water temperature and water height. There is no observable pattern between the points - they seem to simply clump up at the most common temperatures and wave heights, with a few outliers here or there. The correlation coefficient of a graph of this nature would be close to zero, as there are no signs of the data following any sort of pattern or line. Further, because the data set is so large, a significant conclusion can be reached, because any outliers will have been properly factored in, allowing for a much smaller margin of error. As such, we can conclude that there is no observable trend between water temperature and wave height. A potential shortcoming of this data set could be the multisource variability problem. Because were collecting data from many different beaches, our models may not be conclusive, though this is unlikely as the data still remains extremely clumped without significant outliers. With this information arises the question: what is wave height affected by? Simply looking at the data set, it seems that wave height only has a direct correlation with wave period. We could confirm this by creating another scatterplot to search for any linear relationships between the two variables. In summation, because there is no observable linear relationship between water temperature and wave height, its clear that no conclusion can be drawn about the data.

From this graph, we could see that by divided the graph into three segements. We could see that there is a possible correlation between water temperature and turbidity in the fisrt segement. Thus we filter out water temperature less than 16 to look closely at the first segment.

beach_mod = beach1 %>% filter(water_temp < 16)
turb_lm = lm(log10(turbidity)~log10(water_temp), data = beach_mod)
cf_turb = coef(turb_lm)
slope_turb = cf_turb[2]
intercept_turb = cf_turb[1]
resid_turb = residuals(turb_lm)
summary(turb_lm)
